# Next.js Frontend Rules

## App Router File Structure
- Use Next.js 13+ App Router structure
- Pages go in `app/` directory with `page.tsx` files
- Layouts use `layout.tsx` files
- Loading states use `loading.tsx` files
- Error boundaries use `error.tsx` files
- Components go in `components/` directory
- Utilities go in `lib/` directory

## API Integration
- **NEVER use mock data** - always fetch from real backend
- ALL API calls must go through `/lib/api.ts`
- Use proper error handling for all API calls
- Implement retry logic for critical API calls

## Required Loading and Error States
- Every data fetch operation MUST have loading and error states
- Use `loading.tsx` files for page-level loading
- Use `Suspense` boundaries for component-level loading
- Implement error boundaries with `error.tsx` files
- Show user-friendly error messages

## Authentication
- Auth context must be provided at root layout level
- JWT tokens stored in memory ONLY - never localStorage
- Implement token refresh logic
- Redirect unauthenticated users appropriately

## TypeScript Standards
- Strict mode enabled
- NO `any` types allowed - use proper typing
- Use interface definitions for all data structures
- Prefer type unions over any
- Use generic types where appropriate

## Deferred Features
The following features are explicitly deferred and should NOT be implemented:
- Mobile responsive design (focus on iPad web browser only)
- Complex animations or transitions
- Accessibility features (a11y)
- Dark mode theming
- Multi-language support
- Advanced responsive breakpoints

## Component Structure
- Use functional components with hooks
- Implement proper prop typing
- Use React.memo for performance optimization where needed
- Follow single responsibility principle

## State Management
- Use React Context for global state
- Prefer built-in hooks (useState, useEffect) over external libraries
- Implement custom hooks for reusable logic
- Keep state as close to components that need it as possible

## Performance
- Implement code splitting with dynamic imports
- Use Next.js Image component for all images
- Implement proper caching strategies
- Minimize bundle size

## Error Handling
- Implement global error boundary
- Log errors appropriately
- Provide fallback UI for errors
- Handle network errors gracefully